This portion of our conversation almost moved me to tears. Here’s to moms everywhere! I spoke to trailblazing business leader and all-around badass Ursula Burns. When she became the CEO of @xerox in 2009, she was the first Black female CEO of a Fortune 500 company. There’s so much more to Ursula’s career and life story aside from her historic achievement, which is movingly detailed in her memoir, "Where You Are is Not Who You Are." In it, she opens up about her childhood growing up in public housing in New York City, her Catholic-school days, her marriage, and, yes, her 30-year ascent to the tippy top of Xerox’s ladder. Listen to our full conversation wherever you get your #podcasts!

node.text:
More than a dozen states have enacted nearly 30 restrictive voting laws since the 2020 election, according to a June tally by the Brennan Center for Justice. President Biden gave an impassioned speech in Philidelphia today, calling the attack on voting rights “the most significant test” of American democracy since the Civil War.

During the speech, President Biden stressed the importance of passing the John Lewis Voting Rights Act, and called on Congress to repair “the damage done” by the Supreme Court’s decision to weaken the Voting Rights Act. He also criticized Republicans for opposing the For The People Act. 

"Some things in America should be simple and straightforward. Perhaps the most important of those things, the most fundamental of those things, is the right to vote. The right to vote freely... The right to vote fairly, the right to have your vote counted. The Democratic threshold is liberty. With it, anything is possible. Without it, nothing,” the President said. Did you catch the speech -- and if so, what did you think of it? Let me know! #politics #biden #vote #votingrights #news

node.text: Grief can be such a lonely and isolating experience. Keith Davidson, a 95 year old retired judge, was devastated when he lost his wife Abby of 66 years in 2016. But he was able to turn his grief into something so special for his community. You’re an amazing man, Judge Davidson. ♥️♥️ #love #happymonday #goodnews

node.text: In a ceremony full of moving moments, one of the most moving was @carriecmonahan serenading the happy couple with Songbird, and later preforming at the reception with her handsome counterpart, David, Mark’s brother and best man. I ❤️ Mary Karr. We're kicking off my bonus summer book series with the boss of memoir herself, Mary Karr. In 1995, Mary published her debut memoir, “The Liar’s Club” -- which took the publishing world by storm and inspired a wave of confessional memoirs. Since then, Mary has written two more memoirs, a how-to book about the genre called “The Art of Memoir,” and five celebrated volumes of poetry. Oh, and did I mention she’s currently working on her fourth memoir!?

We dive into it all — the writing process, books that impacted Mary’s life and career, aging gracefully (or not), and so much more. Listen wherever you get your podcasts — and let me know what you think of the series!🤓📚📖

It’s the last day of #pridemonth so I wanted to share a clip from my @natgeo documentary “Gender Revolution. Five years ago, I set out to explore and learn more about the rapidly evolving complexities of gender identity. It was hard for me to wrap my head around how much things have changed. Ally was one of the many heroic people I met while filming — and I wanted to share her story with you all. I also met Kristina Olsen, director of the @transyouthproject - an incredible organization that is conducting a 20 year longitudinal study of transgender and gender non conforming children in the US. I checked in with Kristina to see how her study was going, and she shared a few updates:
◽️The project is continuing to go well. We’re still running it (via Zoom through COVID!) The oldest kids just hit formal adulthood though the youngest are still in elementary school.
◽️We have replicated our initial findings on mental health with later cohorts, meaning we are still finding that our kids mental health is good. They have totally average/normal rates of depression and only a very slight elevation in anxiety to other kids on average. We’ve also found that kids who are most supported (by their families, schools, etc) tend to be doing the best in terms of mental health. 
◽️Nearly all the kids in the study continue to identify as trans, though a small number today identify as non-binary (a term most wouldn’t have known back when Gender Revolution was filmed).
◽️The broader social context has shifted a lot since this story aired. Many more people are aware of the existence of trans youth, but there’s also been considerable public pushback with the wave of anti-trans bills and court decisions, especially in the US and UK. Kristina writes: “My sense if that this is how a lot of social change happens — two steps forward, one step back. But it’s hard on families living in the moment. An anti-trans bill in one state may not hold in the long run, but if it’s in effect for four years, that may be a given kid’s whole high school years.”
Kristina wrote a piece about the recent anti-trans bills and the effects they will have on trans children for the @scientific_american.

I'm so proud of my friend Gavin Grimm -- whom I had the pleasure of meeting in 2017 while filming my @natgeo documentary Gender Revolution. Yesterday, he won a years-long legal battle against his former high school in Virginia over its refusal to let him use the boys bathroom when he was a student. The US Supreme Court rejected the Gloucester County School Board's appeal of a lower court decision that found its transgender bathroom ban is unconstitutional. "I was barred from the bathroom at my high school 7 years ago, when I was 15," Gavin wrote in a tweet yesterday. "6 years ago, at 16, myself with the @aclu_nationwide and @acluva filed suit in response to that discrimination. Twice since I have enjoyed victories in court, and now it's over. We won." 

PS: If you want to watch "Gender Revolution" (which you should do because it's almost the end of Pride Month!!) you can stream it on @disneyplus or for free on my Facebook page! #pride #transrights #news

On June 26, 2015 - the Supreme Court ruled in a 5-4 decision that the Constitution guarantees a right to same-sex marriage in all 50 states. "No longer may this liberty be denied," Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote for the majority in the historic decision. "No union is more profound than marriage, for it embodies the highest ideals of love, fidelity, devotion, sacrifice, and family. In forming a marital union, two people become something greater than once they were." Back in 2015, I interviewed Jim Obergefell, who was the plaintiff at the heart of this Supreme Court case. 

According to the US census, more than half of the country’s nearly one million same sex partner households are now married. And a Gallup poll recently found that 70% of the American public, including for the first time a majority of Republicans, now support equal marriage rights.

Thinking of Jim and the countless other individuals who fought so hard for the right to love and marry whomever they wanted to. 🏳️‍🌈 #pride #loveisloveislove

Have you all been following our "Leading With Love" series with @proctergamble?! In our final video, we meet Pastor Rudy Rasmus, who wants the homeless population of Houston, Texas to know that they are not alone. His charity, @breadoflifehoutx, helps the most vulnerable citizens of Houston through a partnership with the humanitarian aid organization @m25m_org. Using donations from Procter & Gamble, the two organizations have helped Houston’s homeless through some of the most difficult crises in recent history, from Hurricane Harvey in 2017 to the cold front that slammed Texas this past winter. Thank you, Pastor Rudy, for reminding us that a life of service is a life worth living. 
#leadwithlove #pgpartner

This clip is devastating for so many reasons. On Saturday, a shooting near Nationals Park in Washington DC sent players and fans scrambling for safety in the middle of a baseball game. In this clip, Faris Nunn, an eight year old, was sitting by third base in Nationals Park with her family when shots rang out. Her response to how she was feeling after the terrifying ordeal just breaks my heart. “It was my second shooting, so I was kinda prepared….I always am expecting something to happen.”

It was just one of many shootings that occurred over the weekend — in Chicago, at least 53 people were shot in 41 separate shootings from Friday evening to Sunday evening; In Philly, two people were injured, including a one year old boy in shoo-ins over the weekend; in DC, the shooting outside the Nationals stadium injured three people, including a fan who was waiting for an Uber outside the stadium; one woman died and six other people were wounded in a shooting in downtown Portland, Oregon early Saturday morning. node.text:
Some of you may remember my friend Sarah (@soos21), who I met in May of last year. Last February, Sarah was diagnosed with an aggressive form of breast cancer, and had to undergo an intense regimen of treatments during the height of the pandemic. This has been a very difficult and challenging journey for Sarah, and I’ve asked her to share an update on how she’s doing (see below). I love my followers. Can you all send her a message of love, encouragement and support below? It will make her day!!!💗 

From Sarah:
After 16 months of IV chemotherapy, a double mastectomy, radiation, oral chemotherapy, a full hysterectomy and a random tumor found on my abdomen during surgery (gotta keep me on my toes, right?), I’m officially considered in remission. Because triple-negative breast cancer is aggressive and I’m BRCA1, there’s a higher risk of recurrence. I’m starting new drug for 1 year to hopefully reduce those chances.

I’m struggling emotionally and physically, which I know is normal. My body hurts, I’m fatigued, I’m sensitive, I’m fearful. A part of me feels as if I have no femininity left - my boobs are gone, my reproductive system is gone, my hair is awkward, I’ve gained 25 lbs. I look in the mirror sometimes and I just… cry.

Sadie (who’s in the last pic!) has been my happy place since I adopted her. She’s just the sweetest 9-year-old gal who fills my heart with so much joy. I look at her, smile and just feel… calm. It’s a classic case of “who saved who.” 

PS. From Katie again:  your responses make me cry. Thank you all. Restores my faith in humanity. ❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️ (And this post is for all of you struggling, feeling lonely and scared. We care. Whoever you are. Wherever you are. And whatever you are dealing with.)

node.text: Hey everyone, I told Molner only a couple more days of wedding photos but there are a few things I still want to highlight. In addition to the wedding party, the flowers were the star of the show. You all know how much I love flowers, as does Ellie (seems to run in the family, my mom arranged flowers for weddings with a group of women we called “the flower ladies”). So we were VERY excited about picking out all the blooms! We worked with a very talented floral designer named Ingrid from @tincanstudios who is a true artist. For an interview with Ingrid and a glimpse into our multiflorous vision, get the scoop in our Saturday edition of Wake-Up Call — go to katiecouric.com or click the link in my bio! This portion of our conversation almost moved me to tears. Here’s to moms everywhere! I spoke to trailblazing business leader and all-around badass Ursula Burns. When she became the CEO of @xerox in 2009, she was the first Black female CEO of a Fortune 500 company. There’s so much more to Ursula’s career and life story aside from her historic achievement, which is movingly detailed in her memoir, "Where You Are is Not Who You Are." In it, she opens up about her childhood growing up in public housing in New York City, her Catholic-school days, her marriage, and, yes, her 30-year ascent to the tippy top of Xerox’s ladder. Listen to our full conversation wherever you get your #podcasts!
